# Project Instructions — Monolith-Enabled

This project uses the **Monolith** plugin for Unreal Engine MCP integration.

## Available MCP Tools

Monolith exposes ~14 namespace tools instead of 119 individual tools:

- `monolith.discover(namespace?)` — List available actions (call this first)
- `monolith.status()` — Health check, index status, version
- `monolith.reindex()` — Trigger full project re-index
- `blueprint.query(action, params)` — Blueprint graph inspection (5 actions)
- `material.query(action, params)` — Material editing and creation (14 actions)
- `animation.query(action, params)` — Animation asset workflows (23 actions)
- `niagara.query(action, params)` — Niagara particle systems (39 actions)
- `editor.query(action, params)` — Build, logs, compile output, crash context (13 actions)
- `config.query(action, params)` — Config/INI resolution (6 actions)
- `source.query(action, params)` — Engine source lookup (10 actions)
- `project.query(action, params)` — Deep project index search (5 actions)

## Workflow

1. Use `monolith.discover("namespace")` to see available actions before calling
2. Use `project.query("search", {"query": "..."})` to find assets across the project
3. Use domain-specific tools to inspect and modify assets
4. Use `editor.query("get_build_errors")` after builds to diagnose issues

## Asset Path Conventions

All asset paths use `/Game/Path/To/Asset` format (no `.uasset` extension):
- Project `Content/`: `/Game/Path/To/Asset`
- Project `Plugins/`: `/PluginName/PluginName/Path/To/Asset`
- Engine plugins: `/PluginName/Path/To/Asset`

## Rules

- Always discover available actions before guessing action names
- The project index is pre-built — use `project.query` for broad searches
- Engine source lookups via `source.query` work offline against the local index
- Never guess `#include` paths or function signatures — use `source.query` to verify
- After modifying C++, check build results with `editor.query("get_build_errors")`
